AWS S3 to Transcribe Lambda Function
This Lambda function automatically triggers an AWS Transcribe job whenever a new MP3 audio file is uploaded to a designated Amazon S3 bucket. The transcribed text will then be saved back to the same S3 bucket.

How it Works
S3 Event Trigger: The Lambda function is configured to be triggered by an S3 event (specifically, s3:ObjectCreated:Put).
File Retrieval: When an MP3 file is uploaded to the monitored S3 bucket, the Lambda function receives the event, extracts the bucket name and file key.
Transcription Job: It then initiates an AWS Transcribe job for the uploaded audio file.
Output: The transcribed text (in JSON format) is stored in the same S3 bucket as the original audio file.
Setup
Prerequisites
An AWS account.
Basic understanding of AWS Lambda, S3, and Transcribe.
1. Create an S3 Bucket
If you don't already have one, create an S3 bucket to store your audio files. This bucket will also be where the transcription output is saved.

2. Create an IAM Role for Lambda
Create an IAM role that your Lambda function will assume. This role needs the following permissions:

s3:GetObject: To read the audio file from the S3 bucket.
s3:PutObject: To write the transcription output back to the S3 bucket.
transcribe:StartTranscriptionJob: To initiate transcription jobs.
logs:CreateLogGroup, logs:CreateLogStream, logs:PutLogEvents: For CloudWatch logging.
